```typescript
// TypeScript - OCP with Strategy Pattern
interface DiscountStrategy {
  applyDiscount(price: number): number;
  getDescription(): string;
}

class PercentageDiscount implements DiscountStrategy {
  private percentage: number;

  constructor(percentage: number) {
    this.percentage = percentage;
  }

  applyDiscount(price: number): number {
    return price * (1 - this.percentage / 100);
  }

  getDescription(): string {
    return `${this.percentage}% off`;
  }
}

class FixedAmountDiscount implements DiscountStrategy {
  private amount: number;

  constructor(amount: number) {
    this.amount = amount;
  }

  applyDiscount(price: number): number {
    return Math.max(0, price - this.amount);
  }

  getDescription(): string {
    return `$${this.amount} off`;
  }
}

class BuyOneGetOneFreeDiscount implements DiscountStrategy {
  applyDiscount(price: number): number {
    // Simplified: assume price is for one item, and second is free
    return price / 2; // For two items, effectively 50% off each
  }

  getDescription(): string {
    return `Buy One Get One Free`;
  }
}

class ShoppingCart {
  private items: { name: string; price: number }[];
  private discountStrategy: DiscountStrategy | null;

  constructor() {
    this.items = [];
    this.discountStrategy = null;
  }

  addItem(name: string, price: number) {
    this.items.push({ name, price });
  }

  setDiscountStrategy(strategy: DiscountStrategy) {
    this.discountStrategy = strategy;
  }

  calculateTotalPrice(): number {
    let total = this.items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);
    if (this.discountStrategy) {
      total = this.discountStrategy.applyDiscount(total);
    }
    return total;
  }

  getDiscountDescription(): string {
    return this.discountStrategy ? this.discountStrategy.getDescription() : 'No discount applied.';
  }
}

// Usage:
// const cart = new ShoppingCart();
// cart.addItem('Laptop', 1000);
// cart.addItem('Mouse', 50);

// cart.setDiscountStrategy(new PercentageDiscount(10));
// console.log(`Total after ${cart.getDiscountDescription()}: $${cart.calculateTotalPrice()}`); // 945

// cart.setDiscountStrategy(new FixedAmountDiscount(20));
// console.log(`Total after ${cart.getDiscountDescription()}: $${cart.calculateTotalPrice()}`); // 1030

// cart.setDiscountStrategy(new BuyOneGetOneFreeDiscount()); // For simplicity assumes 2 items for this logic
// cart.addItem('Shirt', 40);
// console.log(`Total after ${cart.getDiscountDescription()}: $${cart.calculateTotalPrice()}`); // (1000+50+40)/2 = 545
```
Adding a new discount type (e.g., `LoyaltyDiscount`) would only require creating a new class implementing `DiscountStrategy`, without modifying the `ShoppingCart` class, thus adhering to OCP.

Violating LSP example:
```java
class Vehicle {
    void startEngine() { /* default implementation */ }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    @Override
    void startEngine() { /* car specific engine start */ }
}

class Bicycle extends Vehicle {
    @Override
    void startEngine() { 
        // Bicycles don't have engines, this method throws an exception or does nothing, 
        // breaking the expectation of clients using 'Vehicle'.
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Bicycle has no engine.");
    }
}
```

Adhering to LSP example (avoiding `startEngine` in `Vehicle`):
```java
interface Movable {
    void move();
}

class Vehicle implements Movable {
    // Common vehicle properties/methods
    public void move() { System.out.println("Vehicle is moving."); }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    public void startEngine() { System.out.println("Car engine started."); }
    @Override
    public void move() { System.out.println("Car is driving."); }
}

class Bicycle extends Vehicle {
    public void pedal() { System.out.println("Bicycle is being pedaled."); }
    @Override
    public void move() { System.out.println("Bicycle is cycling."); }
}

// Client code can now use Movable without issues:
public class Transporter {
    public void transport(Movable item) {
        item.move();
    }
}
```
In the LSP-adherent example, `Movable` defines an action common to all implementers, ensuring that any `Movable` object can be used without unexpected behavior.

